article.headline: Princeton 60, Pennsylvania 59 (OT)
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Justin Conway scored 21 points including the game-winning layup with 2.5 seconds remaining in overtime Tuesday night as Princeton defeated Penn 60-59. Ibrahim Jaaber, who led all scorers with 26 points, had given Penn a 59-58 lead with a foul shot with 9 seconds remaining. Princeton's (12-15, 10-4 Ivy League) Scott Greenman dribbled down the right side and found Conway under the basket. Penn's David Whitehurst threw up a long 3-pointer that fell short at the buzzer. Penn (20-8, 12-2), which clinched the Ivy League title and the league's automatic NCAA tournament berth last weekend, rallied from an 18-point second-half deficit to tie the game on two foul shots by Jaaber with 24 seconds left. Jaaber, held to two points on 1-for-8 shooting in the first half, gave Penn its first lead of the game when he made one of two foul shots to begin overtime. Penn later led 58-54 but Princeton tied the game on two free throws by Conway and a drive by Noah Savage. Princeton dominated in the first half and led by 18 points early in the second half before Penn shaved 16 points off the lead. But the Quakers could not get the right combination of a basket and a defensive stop to tie the game until they overcame a 49-42 deficit in the final 1:12.
